This specification outlines the development of a localized American Football Scoreboard System designed specifically for OBS (Open Broadcaster Software) overlays. The application uses a "Controller-Client" architecture to ensure the operator can update stats on one screen while the broadcast feed updates in real-time on another.

1. Technical Stack
Framework: Svelte (for high reactivity and small bundle size).

Styling: Tailwind CSS (utility-first for rapid UI development).

State Sync: BroadcastChannel API (allows real-time communication between the Controller tab and the Overlay tab without a backend/database).

Deployment: Localhost (intended to be run via npm run dev or a local build).

2. Functional Requirements: The Data Model
The application must track and sync the following "Source of Truth" state:

Score & Possession
Team Names: String (Home/Away).

Score: Integer (0–99).

Possession: Boolean/Toggle (Indicator for which team has the ball).

Timeouts Remaining (TOT): Integer (3 per team, per half).

Clocks & Game State
Game Clock: MM:SS format (Starts at 15:00 or 12:00, toggleable Start/Stop).

Play Clock: Integer (Starts at 40 or 25, auto-resets).

Quarter: 1, 2, 3, 4, OT.

Down & Distance: E.g., "3rd & 7".

Ball On: String/Integer (e.g., "Own 25" or "Opp 10").

3. UI/UX: The Controller (Admin View)
The Controller is the operator's dashboard. It should be optimized for "tap" interactions (tablet-friendly).

Configuration Panel
Team Branding: * Inputs for Primary Color, Secondary Color, and Text Color.

Color Presets: A grid of the 12 most used football colors:

Red, Navy, Royal Blue, Cyan, Orange, Dark Green, Purple, Silver, White, Maroon, Teal, Pewter.

Quick Selectors: Dedicated large buttons for Black (#000000) and Gold (#FFB612).

Team Names: Editable text fields that sync instantly.

Action Panel (The "Hot" Zone)
Score Buttons: Large +6, +3, +2, +1 and a -1 (for corrections) for each team.

Clock Controls: Large Start/Stop button for the Game Clock. Reset buttons for 40/25 Play Clock.

Possession Toggle: A "Ball" icon that flips between teams.

4. UI/UX: The Display (OBS Overlay)
The Display is a clean, minimal route (/overlay) designed to be pulled into OBS as a Browser Source.

Chroma Key/Transparency: The background of this route must be transparent (bg-transparent).

Layout: Standard "Scorebug" style (horizontal bar at the bottom or top-left corner).

Visual Priority:

Score and Team Abbreviations (most prominent).

Game Clock and Quarter (secondary).

Down/Distance/Play Clock (tertiary).

